{"key":"post-8906197","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8906197</id>\n<content>A search for hay should have returned many threads with lots of reasons not to use it.&amp;nbsp; The seeds are a major reason as they'll contaminate with green molds.&amp;nbsp; Straw is better also because it's hollow and that gives lots of places for mycelium to colonize, as well as a moisture reservoir to support massive flushes, which hay can't provide.&amp;nbsp; Some of the biggest mushrooms we've ever seen around here were grown on straw, so that makes moot the point about 'nutrients'.&amp;nbsp; Below is a micrograph of a cross section of straw, so you can see what I mean.&lt;br /&gt;RR&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://files.shroomery.org/files/07-006/108452877-SEM_of_Straw.jpg&quot; class=&quot;highslide&quot; onclick=&quot;return hs.expand(this,{slideshowGroup:'hsg1'})&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;max-width:192px;height:auto;&quot; src=&quot;/forums/thumbs/07-006/108452877-thumb_SEM_of_Straw.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;/a&gt;</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>8906026</prev>\n<first>8904864</first>\n<last>8906197</last>\n<when>1221063056</when>\n<utime>09/10/08 07:10 PM</utime>\n</post>"}